T1  - Optimal tariffs in consistent conjectural variations equilibrium
AU  - Turnovsky, Stephen J.
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 21
IS  - 3
SP  - 301
EP  - 312
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/11/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(86)90042-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199686900425
AB  - This paper analyzes the determination of the optimal tariff under the assumption of consistent conjectural variations (CCV). A general characterization of the CCV equilibrium is given. We show that (i) there are, in general, a multiplicity of each equilibria, and (ii) under certain restrictions, the Cournot equilibrium, which is based on the assumption of no retaliation, can also be a CCV equilibrium. By contrast, free trade is never a CCV equilibrium. Finally, the CCV equilibrium is solved explicitly in a simple example.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Tariffs, subsidies, and welfare with endogenous policy
AU  - Rodrik, Dani
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 21
IS  - 3
SP  - 285
EP  - 299
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/11/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(86)90041-3
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199686900413
AB  - It is a well-established proposition of trade theory that in the absence of directly trade-related distortions or policy goals subsidies are superior to tariffs for achieving any economic or non-economic objective. This paper shows that once the endogeneity of the distortion or non-economic objective is allowed for, the welfare-ranking of various policies can be reversed. The particular model analyzed is one where the level of non-economic objectives that have to be fulfilled itself depends on the policy tools considered to fulfill them with. This arises from the public-good nature of tariffs compared to subsidies.
ER  - 

