DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(86)90047-4
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199686900474
AB  - In a recent article, Helpman (1984) develops readily testable bilateral restrictions in a model of international trade which preserves the spirit of Heckscher-Ohlin trade theory. Important in any empirical exploration of the Heckscher-Ohlin model is the decision of whether to employ direct or direct-plus-indirect calculations in determining the factor content of trade. This paper extends Helpman's analysis to a world of freely traded intermediate goods, and shows that direct factor content calculations are the theoretically appropriate measure for use in evaluating these empirical implications of the Heckscher-Ohlin model.
ER  - 

