DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(86)90046-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199686900462
AB  - This paper examines optimal taxation of foreign capital by a host country when its movements are sluggish. It is shown that as long as the host country discounts future welfare it is optimal to tax foreign capital even when it is small enough to be unable to influence the reward to capital in the source country. This is because the initial gains from taxing foreign capital constitute rent transfer from foreign capital owners to the host country, which outweighs the future losses in terms of reduced output.
